title Pool P1 landed GREEN — two agents, one capability boundary, isolation witnessed
prompt Keaton said "kg" (keep-going) after Pool P0 landed green; the recommend line named P1 (two agents, one capability boundary) as the next lap.
think stacked P1 on the same branch as P0 (unsent, awaiting send) so the two ship together, rather than branching from an unmerged base.
think extended pool_host_seam.rye additively with host_agent_on(table, agent, state_resource, log, ...) -- the generalization P1 needs: each agent's state is its own named resource, so admission to one says nothing about another. Left P0's host_ledger_agent untouched so the P0 witness stays byte-stable and green (confirmed by re-run).
think modeled the isolation guarantee as a capability boundary rather than an ambient sandbox: agent-a owns state-a (rw), agent-b owns state-b (rw); each folds only its own state, and cross-access is refused unless the table explicitly grants it. This is the honest microkernel shape -- isolation IS the capability table, not a separate mechanism -- and it is exactly what the brief said P1 must witness.
think made the two states genuinely distinct (log_b = welcome + one extra signed send, so issuer 250/holder 750 vs A's 200/800) so "independent state" is shown by different folds, not merely asserted.
think wrote five falsifiable claims, green first try: each agent folds its own independent state; agent-a refused at agent-b's state; agent-b refused at agent-a's state (mutual); an explicit grant to agent-a over state-b is the ONLY thing that opens cross-access; and that grant does not leak back the other way (agent-b still refused at state-a). The mutual-and-non-leaking pair is the load-bearing part -- it proves the boundary is real in both directions and does not spill.
think wired P1 into parity_ch01.rish after P0 and re-ran both Pool witnesses -- both GREEN, confirming the additive host_agent_on did not disturb P0.
obs the capability boundary sound from the first witness is the thing I flagged earlier as Pool's largest risk (every agent above inherits any flaw); P1 witnesses it directly -- no cross-access without a named, granted capability, and grants do not leak.
obs "kg" is keep-going, not "send" -- so P0 and P1 both rest on the branch awaiting Keaton's send word.
